reviews.review_text: Cilantro was great. However, I wish the Walmart shopper would have placed it in a produce bag. Instead in was placed in grocery bag with 5 other items. I’d rather not add to any germs that it may already have from the grower to the produce bin in the store. ………….WALMART, PLEASE EDUCATE YOUR SHOPPERS TO BAG ALL UNWRAPPED PRODUCE. SAFETY FIRST!!!

reviews.title: Parsley is not cilantro
reviews.review_text: Many times when I order cilantro, I receive parsley. It says parsley right on the tag, but for some reason, it keeps getting delivered to me instead of cilantro. If you can speak to your shopper, have them be diligent about what they’re choosing. It’s just plain lack of consideration.

reviews.title: Spoiled cilantro
reviews.review_text: When I brought my groceries inside my cilantro was brown, spoked and had a bad smell. I know it’s not an expensive item but now I don’t have all the ingredients for the dish I am making and it requires me to go to the store myself which is what I wanted to prevent.

reviews.title: Slimy
reviews.review_text: Wish I could give it zero stars. I understand that workers need to shop fast to make quota etc BUT I feel that they need to remember not to put anything into a person’s order they wouldn’t want to purchase themselves. It was mostly slimy and rotting.

reviews.title: Cilantro
reviews.review_text: Used Walmart pick-up and cilantro product would have been fine….cilantro was soaked with at least 3/4 cup of mud and muddy fluid. Do not know where the Walmart employee picked product from but it was totally disgusting and unacceptable. Water and mud filled clear vegetable bag, soaking all of cilantro leaves and stems in mud. Unable to even consider washing. Employees need better training on what is acceptable to sell/charge a customer. Recently received already rotten green onions on a pick up order. Enough is enough. Train employees and supervise them.

reviews.title: Pre-crushed (and rolled?) cilantro

Maybe the current person selecting produce should be a greeter, or at least have some basic training. Bring back your old produce person! The quality and handling of delivery orders has been going downhill quickly. Issues with delivery orders used to be rare. Now, I wonder, "What will be the issue this time and how much will it cost me?" You can do better. Do better.

reviews.title: Unusable item, bad quality

I'm very disappointed with the shoppers and especially the produce manager.

reviews.title: FRESH AND TASTY
reviews.review_text: Arrives amazingly fresh in a nice, big bunch. Cilantro loses quality very quickly when cut. This arrived fresh as can be. Cut the ends even, put them in a glass of water, cover with the baggie it arrived in, refrigerate to use as needed. Lasts a week.

reviews.title: Fresh, fragrant, very food condition.
reviews.review_text: Wanted to try after many years to see if my tastes changed. Still don't care for cilantro (aka Chinese parsley). Chopped it up to make pico de gallo, but I prefer the milder flavor profile of parsley. It wasn't bad, and I'd eat it again, but I'll instead use parsley in the future. This product was very fresh. No brown leaves. Fragrant (more than I care for). If I liked cilantro, I'd buy this again based on flavor and quality.

reviews.title: Wilted cilantro
reviews.review_text: Very wilted and "wimpy". Usually very good item from Walmart. Don't know if this was an old bunch - or picker simply did not closely look at what they were selecting. It certainly did not appear fresh. Price not enough to bother with trying to get more cilantro.

Every time I select a pick up that contains cilantro or any trip of produce I get the worst, rotten, or withering items. Not sure if this is what they are instructed to do but it never fails. After the 3rd attempt I'm done ordering produce online. The cilantro is usually pretty good and have a lot to choose from but not when ordering online

reviews.title: Cilantro and Parsley are not the same thing
reviews.review_text: So, my “cilantro” arrived looking like parsley’s evil twin. I dropped $5 plus a tip for a 3-hour delivery to avoid the dreaded trip to the store… guess who’s making that trip now? Spoiler: it’s me. Honestly, I blame the delivery driver’s mom—somebody should’ve taught him cilantro and parsley aren’t just fancy salad decorations!

reviews.title: Small but Tasty
reviews.review_text: We buy a lot of cilantro online and the way it looks varies greatly with harvests. This was good but was short and had very small leaves as if very new growth or it was getting ready to bloom. Either way, it's still good and looks fresh. Next order might be extra large leaves. As long as it's fresh, it's all good

reviews.title: Good *most* of the time
reviews.review_text: We do delivery from the store for our groceries, and nine times out of ten, we have no issues with the Cilantro—it's fresh, crispy, fragrant, and typically pretty generous in leaves. Basically, it's exactly what you'd expect to receive. I docked one star because the other 10% of the time, you'll end up with something that looks like it was forgotten at the bottom of the box for a few days, and it arrives ready to be tossed out and inedible.

It looked like someone had smashed the cilantro causing it to be badly bruised [r it was old but the leaves that were not "smashed looked good,and the part that was usable tasted good. I would be willing to try to use this product again to give it a fair chance.

reviews.title: “Lather me up, baby!“
reviews.review_text: This cilantro is like that one friend who crashes the party and suddenly everyone's salsa is better, the guac is vibing, and your taco is doing the cha-cha. It's fresh, it's zesty, it's basically edible confetti for your mouth. Sure, some people say it tastes like soap — but I say, “Lather me up, baby!“

reviews.title: Cilantro... I can't believe they got it right!
reviews.review_text: I was so happy to order cilantro from Walmart Plus and actually receive cilantro and not flat leaf Italian parsley. Also, I was astounded that it was so fresh and not wilted, bruised or slimy. They say miracles can happen, and today they happened with my Walmart Plus order. Thank you to the shopper who got it right the first time!

reviews.title: fesh and green almost always.
reviews.review_text: always fresh, which is a good thing. one thing is that the bunch should be tighly packed. For most dishes ,it is an essential ingredient when you cut the leaves and sprinkle on top of the dishes specially 'Aalo Gosht'.

reviews.title: A Cooking Essential

I just wish it would last longer even though I wrap it in a paper towel covered with foil. Oh, don't forget to use the stems! Pop the in a freezer bag, or blend and put in an ice cube tray to freeze. Then, in winter, you can add it to soups, etc.

Bleah.

reviews.title: Fresh, Fragrant, and Perfect for My Recipes
reviews.review_text: This cilantro was crisp, vibrant green, and bursting with that fresh, citrusy aroma I love. The leaves were tender, the stems sturdy, and there was no wilting or yellowing. I used it to make a fresh corn salsa and also stirred it into homemade cilantro lime white rice—both turned out flavorful and bright. It stayed fresh in my fridge for nearly a week when I stored it in a glass of water. Excellent quality and a must-have for anyone who loves cooking with fresh herbs!
